"""
mkt-christ — Numbers chapter 6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-numbers-6-6.py

Two sections:
  vv.1-21: Nazirite vow — shadow/type of Christ's total consecration to YHWH
  vv.22-27: Aaronic Blessing — type/fulfillment in Christ as the face of God

Key Christological connections:
- Nazirite as type of Christ's unique, total consecration (Heb 7:26: holy,
  innocent, unstained, separated from sinners)
- v.7: family ties cannot interrupt the consecration — Luke 2:49; Mark 3:31-35
- v.11: Nazirite defiled needs a sin offering; Christ is without sin (Heb 4:15)
  and needs no such purification — the contrast reveals his perfection
- v.18: hair burned under fellowship offering — Christ's entire humanity given up
- vv.14-17: all three sacrifice types at completion: olah/chatta't/shelamim →
  Christ's total consecration, expiation, and restored communion
- v.25: 'face shine' → 2 Cor 4:6 (glory of God in the face of Christ)
- v.27: name placed on Israel → baptismal name of the Trinity; Rev 22:4

Note: v.24 already exists in the output — merge_comm will skip it.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The Nazirite legislation opens the chapter that culminates in the Aaronic blessing — a deliberate progression from individual voluntary consecration to priestly blessing of the whole community. Both sections address the mediation of YHWH's holiness: the Nazirite reaches up toward YHWH's holiness through self-imposed separation; the priests reach down with YHWH's blessing toward Israel. Christ fulfills both movements: he is the one who consecrates himself completely (John 17:19: 'for their sake I consecrate myself') and the one who blesses (Luke 24:50-51).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Nazirite vow is voluntary: anyone — man or woman — may choose to set themselves apart for YHWH. The verb <em>yafli</em> (to separate, set apart, make extraordinary) derives from <em>pele</em> (wonder, extraordinary thing). The Nazirite performs an act of extraordinary devotion — going beyond what covenant law requires. This shadow of voluntary, surpassing consecration finds its fulfillment in Christ, who did not merely fulfill the law's minimum requirements but gave himself completely (Phil 2:7-8: 'emptying himself... becoming obedient to death, even death on a cross').</p>",
    "3": "<p>The triple grape prohibition (wine, vinegar, fresh/dried grapes) separates the Nazirite from the ordinary social world of Canaan — the world of feasting, hospitality, and celebration. Christ too separated himself from ordinary social rhythms for the sake of his mission: he ate with sinners (Mark 2:15-17), but he also fasted forty days (Matt 4:2) and kept vigils in prayer (Luke 6:12). The Nazirite's total abstinence from the grape is a shadow of Christ's total consecration to his Father's will, which sometimes required separation from ordinary human pleasures.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Even the seeds and skins of the grape — the residue of winemaking — are forbidden to the Nazirite during the vow period. The comprehensiveness signals total separation: not merely from wine's effects but from the grape itself in every form. Christ's consecration was similarly total: he was 'holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners' (Heb 7:26) — not partially clean or mostly devoted, but wholly set apart in every dimension of his humanity for the Father's purposes.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'No razor shall touch his head. The Nazirite is holy to the LORD.' The uncut hair is the visible sign of total consecration on the body — a crown of living dedication. The phrase <em>qadosh hu la-YHWH</em> (he is holy to YHWH) applies to the Nazirite precisely because of this bodily sign. Christ, the Holy One of God (John 6:69; Luke 1:35), is the antitype: he is inherently, essentially holy — not by vow but by nature. The Nazirite's temporary, externally-marked holiness is a creaturely shadow of Christ's eternal and intrinsic holiness.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Nazirite shall not go near a dead body — a purity requirement at the high-priestly level (cf. Lev 21:11). Christ was not defiled by contact with the dead; on the contrary, his touch reversed the defilement: he raised Lazarus (John 11:43-44), raised Jairus's daughter (Mark 5:41-42), and raised the widow's son at Nain (Luke 7:14-15). When Christ touches death, death gives way — the direction of impurity-transfer is reversed. Where the Nazirite must avoid the dead to preserve holiness, Christ goes to the dead and imparts life.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Even if his father, mother, brother, or sister dies, he shall not defile himself, because the sign of God's consecration is on his head.' The vow to YHWH takes precedence over the most urgent family obligations. Christ's mission also superseded family claims in ways that astonished contemporaries: 'Who are my mother and brothers?... Whoever does the will of God is my brother and sister and mother' (Mark 3:33-35). At age twelve: 'Did you not know that I must be about my Father's business?' (Luke 2:49). The Nazirite's family-superseding consecration is a type of Christ's radical devotion to the Father that placed the covenant mission above every other claim.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The Nazirite is holy to the LORD throughout the entire period of his separation.' The holiness is not intermittent but continuous — every day of the vow, without exception. Christ's holiness was likewise continuous and unbroken: he was 'tempted in every way as we are, yet without sin' (Heb 4:15). The Nazirite maintained holiness for a bounded period; Christ maintained it for an entire lifetime under conditions of incarnate vulnerability, poverty, opposition, and ultimate suffering. The Nazirite's temporal total-holiness is a bounded shadow of Christ's eternal and unbroken holiness.</p>",
    "9": "<p>If the Nazirite is accidentally defiled, the entire period is void and must be restarted. The accidental defilement exposes the Nazirite's creaturely fragility: even with good intentions and careful precautions, the Nazirite can be compromised by circumstances beyond his control. Christ had no such vulnerability — he could not be accidentally defiled, because defilement moves from the outside in, and 'what comes out of a person is what defiles him' (Mark 7:20). The Nazirite's susceptibility to unintended defilement highlights by contrast Christ's inviolable purity.</p>",
    "10": "<p>On the eighth day of re-purification, the Nazirite brings birds for his cleansing. The eighth day — the day of new beginning beyond the seven-day creation week — is the day of restart, of new consecration. Christ's resurrection on the eighth day (the first day of the new week, but the eighth day of the cosmic calendar) is the ultimate new beginning after death: the day of ultimate re-consecration, not after accidental defilement but after deliberately bearing the sin of the world.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'The priest shall offer one as a sin offering and the other as a burnt offering and make atonement for him, because he became unclean by contact with the dead.' The Nazirite who is defiled requires a sin offering — expiation for the cultic uncleanness. Christ required no such expiation; he was 'a high priest who is holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners' (Heb 7:26). The Nazirite's need for atonement after defilement is precisely what Christ transcended — he was the sin offering for others without ever needing one for himself.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'He shall devote himself again to the LORD for the full term of his separation and bring a year-old male lamb as a guilt offering. The earlier days shall not count.' The defilement voids all prior days — no partial credit, full restart. The guilt offering (<em>asham</em>) covers the interrupted consecration. The contrast with Christ is complete: his consecration was never interrupted, never defiled, never needed to be restarted. The asham Christ bore was not for his own interrupted consecration but for humanity's interrupted covenant — he bore the guilt offering on behalf of all whose consecration had been voided by sin.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'This is the law of the Nazirite: when the days of his separation are complete, he shall be brought to the entrance of the tent of meeting.' The completion ceremony begins at the threshold of covenantal space — the same site where the consecration was undertaken. Christ's death and resurrection constitute his completion ceremony: the one who was consecrated from eternity completed his earthly mission at the cross ('It is finished,' John 19:30) and entered the heavenly sanctuary as both priest and offering (Heb 9:11-12).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Three sacrifice types mark the completion: one unblemished year-old male lamb for a burnt offering (<em>olah</em>), one unblemished year-old female lamb for a sin offering (<em>chatta't</em>), and one unblemished ram for a fellowship offering (<em>shelamim</em>). Together, these three types represent the fullness of what Christ's one sacrifice accomplishes: total self-offering to the Father (<em>olah</em>), expiation of sin (<em>chatta't</em>), and restored communion between God and humanity (<em>shelamim</em>). The Nazirite's completion ceremony requires all three because human consecration is multidimensional; Christ's one death encompasses all three dimensions perfectly.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The unleavened bread basket accompanies the animal offerings — the same structure as the priestly ordination (Exod 29:2; Lev 8:2). The Nazirite at the completion of the vow performs rites structurally identical to priestly ordination. Christ's 'completion' — his death and resurrection — is his ordination into the permanent Melchizedekan priesthood: 'he was designated by God a high priest after the order of Melchizedek' (Heb 5:10), and the ordination was accomplished not by bread and sacrifice at the tabernacle but by 'the blood of the eternal covenant' (Heb 13:20).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The priest performs the sin offering and burnt offering on behalf of the Nazirite — the priest mediates the completion. Christ is simultaneously the one who completes the vow (the Nazirite, the consecrated one) and the one who mediates it (the priest). Hebrews develops this paradox fully: 'he has no need, like those high priests, to offer sacrifices daily... he did this once for all when he offered up himself' (Heb 7:27). The Nazirite requires a separate priest to mediate his completion offering; Christ is his own priest, offering himself.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The ram as a fellowship offering — the final act of the completion ceremony — marks the Nazirite's reintegration into the community of ordinary life. The <em>shelamim</em> is the meal of covenant relationship: portions for YHWH, portions for the priest, portions for the worshipper — a shared table. Christ's death as a fellowship/peace offering (the <em>shelamim</em> dimension) restores communion between God and humanity: 'through him to reconcile to himself all things, making peace by the blood of his cross' (Col 1:20).</p>",
    "18": "<p>'The Nazirite shall shave his consecrated head and take the hair from his consecrated head and put it on the fire under the fellowship offering.' The hair — the Nazirite's most visible sign of consecration, the bodily crown of his devotion — is burned as the final offering. The most personal element of the vow is given entirely to YHWH. Christ's death is the antitype: his body, the ultimate personal gift, was given up entirely (<em>paradidomi</em> — handed over, surrendered) for the fellowship of humanity with God. The Nazirite burns his hair; the Son of God gives his life.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The priest places the boiled shoulder, one loaf, and one wafer in the Nazirite's hands for the wave offering — the priestly gesture placing portions in the Nazirite's hands echoes the ordination ceremony (Exod 29:24; Lev 8:27). The Nazirite at completion is treated as a quasi-priest: portions placed in hands for waving. Christ, having completed his redemptive mission, 'sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high' (Heb 1:3) — the completion of his work is followed by enthronement. The Nazirite's completion-as-ordination points to Christ's glorification that follows his death.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'After this, the Nazirite may drink wine.' The entire vow period — total abstinence from the grape — is resolved in these six words: the separation ends, the consecration is complete, and the Nazirite re-enters ordinary life. This temporal release finds its ultimate typological counterpart in Christ's own words at the Last Supper: 'I tell you I will not drink again of this fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father's kingdom' (Matt 26:29). Christ voluntarily abstained from the wine of ordinary life and festivity until the kingdom's completion — a Nazirite-like consecration for the duration of his redemptive mission.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'This is the law of the Nazirite who makes a vow' — the closing formula mirrors the opening. The Nazirite's vow is bounded by its terms, completed by its ceremony, and concludes with the offerer returned to ordinary life having fulfilled a temporary, voluntary heightening of consecration. Christ's 'vow' — his incarnate mission — was not temporary in the sense of a bounded human vow, but it was completed: 'I glorified you on earth, having accomplished the work that you gave me to do' (John 17:4). The Nazirite's completion formula points to Christ's finished work.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A new revelation formula introduces the Aaronic blessing — YHWH speaking directly to Moses with a prescription for priestly speech. The transition from the Nazirite (individual voluntary consecration) to the blessing (priestly corporate mediation of divine favor) mirrors the transition in Christ from his own consecrated mission to his ongoing priestly intercession for his people. Having consecrated himself (John 17:19), Christ now blesses — 'he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Tell Aaron and his sons: This is how you are to bless the Israelites.' The blessing is a priestly office — not any Israelite may pronounce it, but only the Aaronic line. Christ, as the great high priest 'after the order of Melchizedek' (Heb 5:6; 7:17), is the ultimate Aaronic fulfillment: he pronounces the blessing with permanent authority that no Aaronic priest could claim. Significantly, Luke 24:50 records that Jesus 'lifted up his hands and blessed them' as he ascended — performing the Aaronic gesture of benediction as his final act before entering the heavenly sanctuary.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The LORD bless you and keep you; the LORD make his face shine on you and be gracious to you; the LORD lift up his countenance upon you and give you peace.' The Aaronic blessing is the most ancient surviving biblical text — preserved on two silver amulets from Ketef Hinnom (c. 600 BCE, Jerusalem). Christ is simultaneously the mediator through whom these blessings flow (Eph 1:3: 'blessed in Christ with every spiritual blessing') and the content of the blessing itself: he is the blessing, the keeping, the face that shines, the grace, and the peace given to Israel and to the world.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'May the LORD make his face shine on you and be gracious to you.' Paul connects the shining face to Christ explicitly: 'the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ' (2 Cor 4:6). The divine face that the Aaronic blessing calls upon to shine is the face that took human form in Jesus of Nazareth. John 1:14-18 makes the same identification: 'the Word became flesh... full of grace and truth... from his fullness we have all received, grace upon grace.' The Nazirite blessing's 'grace' (<em>chen</em>) and the Johannine 'grace upon grace' converge on the same source: the divine face made visible in Christ.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'May the LORD lift up his face toward you and grant you peace.' Christ is the peace: 'he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility' (Eph 2:14). The shalom YHWH grants through the Aaronic blessing is not merely an inner state but a restored covenantal reality — the reconciliation of creature and Creator, the end of the enmity that sin introduced. Christ's death effects this shalom as a historical-cosmic event: 'making peace by the blood of his cross' (Col 1:20). The blessing pronounced over Israel becomes the reality accomplished in the cross.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'They shall put my name on the Israelites, and I will bless them.' The priestly act places YHWH's name on the people. In the new covenant, this name-placing is accomplished through baptism: Christ commands his disciples to baptize 'in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit' (Matt 28:19) — placing the Trinitarian name on the covenant people. The eschatological fulfillment appears in Revelation: 'they will see his face, and his name will be on their foreheads' (Rev 22:4). The Aaronic blessing is thus a shadow of the entire story arc from Israel's covenant identity to the church's baptismal identity to the redeemed community's eschatological identity in YHWH's name.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('christ', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(existing, NUMBERS)
    save_comm('christ', 'numbers', existing)
    count = len(existing.get('6', {}))
    print(f'ch 6: {count} verses in output')
    print('Numbers 6 christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
